1180","1136":"1136","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1155":"1155","about 1200":"circa 1200","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Workinton, Coupland, Westmorland, England":"Coupland, Westmorland, England"},"en":{"1155–1212":"1155–1212","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1180–1255":"1180–1255","1200–1290":"1200–1290","–Male":"Deceased","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1136–Female":"1136–Deceased","about 1180":"about 1180","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","13 November 1200":"13 November 1200","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","1136":"1136","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1155":"1155","about 1200":"about 1200","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Workinton, Coupland, Westmorland, England":"Coupland, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Curwen,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place called Culewen (now Colvend) in Kirkcudbrightshire. The family was early established in Lancashire, where it was often pronounced without the <i>-w-</i>; see   Corrin   and   Currin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Corrin","meanings":["Irish and Manx: shortened form of <i>Mac Torin</i>, from Gaelic <i>mac</i> ‘son (of)’ + Old Norse <i>Thórfinnr</i> (from <i>Thórr</i>, the name of the Scandinavian thunder god, + the ethnic designation <i>Finnr</i>). Compare   Turpin  . This name has occasionally been confused with   Corin  .","English (Lancashire): variant of   Curwen  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Workington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): habitational name from Wormington in Gloucestershire or Berry Wormington in Stanton (also Gloucestershire). Perhaps also from Warmington in Northamptonshire. The placenames derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrma</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Patrick de Curwen, of Workington was born in 1155, in Workington, Cumberland, England, his father, Sir Thomas Fitz Gospatric, Lord of Culwen, of Workington, was 25 and his mother, Lady Amabalis Culwen, was 19. He married Alina Culwer. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1212, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1155–1212":"1155–1212","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1180–1255":"1180–1255","1200–1290":"1200–1290","–Male":"Surnud","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","13 November 1200":"13. november 1200","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","1136":"1136","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1155":"1155","about 1200":"umbes 1200","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Workinton, Coupland, Westmorland, England":"Coupland, Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"1155–1212":"1155–1212","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1180–1255":"1180–1255","1200–1290":"1200–1290","–Male":"Kuollut","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1136–Female":"1136–Kuollut","about 1180":"noin 1180","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","13 November 1200":"13. marraskuuta 1200","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","1136":"1136","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1155":"1155","about 1200":"noin 1200","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland